{
  "What type of friction acts on an object that is not moving?": "",
  "Static friction keeps it still": "",
  "Kinetic friction keeps it still": "",
  "Rolling friction keeps it still": "",
  "Air resistance keeps it still": "",
  "Static friction acts on objects that are not moving relative to the surface. It resists the start of motion and must be overcome before the object can begin sliding.": "",
  "What type of friction acts on an object that is already sliding?": "",
  "Static friction on the object": "",
  "Kinetic friction on the object": "",
  "Gravitational friction on it": "",
  "Magnetic friction on the object": "",
  "Kinetic friction acts on objects that are already in motion (sliding) relative to a surface. It opposes the direction of sliding and is generally less than the maximum static friction.": "",
  "Which is generally greater: maximum static friction or kinetic friction?": "",
  "Kinetic friction is always greater than static": "",
  "They are always exactly equal to each other": "",
  "Maximum static friction is generally greater": "",
  "Neither type of friction is ever greater": "",
  "Maximum static friction is generally greater than kinetic friction. This is why it takes more force to start pushing a heavy box than to keep it sliding once it is already moving.": "",
  "What causes friction between two surfaces?": "",
  "The color difference between the two surfaces": "",
  "The temperature difference between surfaces": "",
  "Microscopic roughness and interlocking of surfaces": "",
  "The magnetic attraction between the surfaces": "",
  "Friction is caused by the microscopic roughness of surfaces. Even surfaces that look smooth have tiny bumps and ridges that interlock and resist sliding when pressed together.": "",
  "In which direction does friction act relative to the motion or attempted motion of an object?": "",
  "In the same direction as the motion or push": "",
  "In the opposite direction of the motion or push": "",
  "Perpendicular to the direction of the motion": "",
  "Friction does not have a specific direction": "",
  "Friction always opposes motion or the tendency to move. If you push a box to the right, friction pushes to the left. If the box slides left, friction pushes right.": "",
  "What happens to friction if you increase the weight pressing two surfaces together?": "",
  "Friction decreases with more weight": "",
  "Friction stays the same regardless": "",
  "Friction increases with more weight": "",
  "Friction disappears with more weight": "",
  "Increasing the weight (normal force) pressing surfaces together increases friction. The microscopic bumps interlock more tightly, making it harder to slide. This is why heavier objects are harder to push.": "",
  "Which surface combination would likely have the most friction?": "",
  "Ice sliding on polished glass surface": "",
  "Rubber sliding on rough concrete surface": "",
  "Oil sliding on a smooth metal surface": "",
  "Teflon sliding on Teflon surface pair": "",
  "Rubber on rough concrete has very high friction because both surfaces are rough and rubber deforms to grip the surface. This is why car tires are made of rubber - they need strong friction for traction.": "",
  "Why is it harder to start pushing a heavy box than to keep it sliding?": "",
  "The box gets lighter once it starts moving": "",
  "Gravity increases when the box starts moving": "",
  "Static friction is greater than kinetic friction": "",
  "The floor becomes smoother during the motion": "",
  "Maximum static friction is greater than kinetic friction. You need more force to overcome static friction and get the box moving. Once sliding, kinetic friction is lower, so less force is needed to keep it going.": "",
  "Does friction always slow objects down?": "",
  "No, friction can also help objects start moving forward": "",
  "Yes, friction always decreases the speed of objects": "",
  "Yes, friction is only a force that slows things down": "",
  "No, friction has no effect on motion whatsoever": "",
  "Friction does not always slow objects down. When you walk, static friction between your shoe and the ground pushes you forward. Without friction, you could not walk or drive at all.": "",
  "What happens to the friction force when you push a stationary object with gradually increasing force?": "",
  "Friction stays zero until the object starts moving": "",
  "Static friction increases to match the push until it breaks": "",
  "Friction immediately reaches its maximum possible value": "",
  "Friction decreases as the applied force gets stronger": "",
  "Static friction adjusts to match the applied force, keeping the object stationary. As you push harder, static friction pushes back equally hard. Only when the push exceeds maximum static friction does the object start moving.": "",
  "What is static friction?": "",
  "Friction that acts on an object already sliding across a surface": "",
  "Friction that prevents a stationary object from starting to move": "",
  "Friction caused by air pushing against a moving object in wind": "",
  "Friction that occurs only between liquid surfaces in contact": "",
  "Static friction is the friction that prevents a stationary object from starting to move. It acts between surfaces that are not sliding relative to each other and can vary in strength up to a maximum value.": "",
  "What is kinetic friction?": "",
  "Friction that keeps objects from starting to move": "",
  "Friction that acts on objects as they slide along a surface": "",
  "Friction that only exists in outer space vacuum": "",
  "Friction caused by magnetic fields between objects": "",
  "Kinetic friction is the friction acting on an object that is already sliding across a surface. It has a constant value for a given pair of surfaces and always opposes the direction of sliding.": "",
  "What does 'coefficient of friction' mean?": "",
  "A number that describes how rough or smooth surfaces are together": "",
  "The total weight of the object resting on a surface in newtons": "",
  "The speed at which the object slides across any surface at all": "",
  "The direction in which the friction force pushes on the object": "",
  "The coefficient of friction is a dimensionless number that represents how much friction exists between two surfaces. Higher values mean more friction. Rubber on concrete has a high coefficient; ice on ice has a low one.": "",
  "What does 'normal force' mean in the context of friction?": "",
  "The perpendicular force a surface exerts on an object": "",
  "The parallel force that slides the object along a surface": "",
  "The gravitational attraction between the Earth and Moon": "",
  "The force of air resistance acting on any moving object": "",
  "The normal force is the force perpendicular to the surface that supports an object. Friction depends directly on the normal force: the greater the normal force, the greater the friction between surfaces.": "",
  "What does 'traction' mean?": "",
  "The grip between a surface and an object due to friction": "",
  "The speed at which an object slides across a surface": "",
  "The weight of an object pressing down on a surface": "",
  "The air resistance acting on a moving vehicle": "",
  "Traction is the grip that friction provides between two surfaces. Good traction means strong friction for control, like rubber tires on dry roads. Poor traction means low friction, like tires on icy roads.": "",
  "What does 'sliding friction' mean?": "",
  "Another name for kinetic friction between surfaces": "",
  "Friction that keeps objects from starting movement": "",
  "Friction between wheels and the ground surface": "",
  "Friction caused by air flowing over the surface": "",
  "Sliding friction is another name for kinetic friction. It occurs when one surface slides over another. It is constant for a given pair of surfaces and always opposes the sliding direction.": "",
  "What is meant by 'rolling friction'?": "",
  "Friction caused by one object rolling over a surface": "",
  "Friction between two flat surfaces sliding together": "",
  "Friction caused by air moving past an object": "",
  "Friction that prevents any object from moving": "",
  "Rolling friction occurs when a round object rolls over a surface, like a wheel on a road. It is generally much less than sliding (kinetic) friction, which is why wheels make it easier to move heavy loads.": "",
  "What does 'lubricant' mean in relation to friction?": "",
  "A substance that increases friction between surfaces": "",
  "A substance that reduces friction between surfaces": "",
  "A substance that measures friction between surfaces": "",
  "A substance that eliminates gravity on the object": "",
  "A lubricant is a substance (like oil or grease) placed between surfaces to reduce friction. It creates a thin layer that prevents the surfaces from directly touching, reducing the resistance to sliding.": "",
  "What does 'surface texture' mean in the study of friction?": "",
  "The roughness or smoothness of a surface": "",
  "The color and brightness of a surface": "",
  "The temperature of the surface material": "",
  "The weight of the surface material itself": "",
  "Surface texture describes how rough or smooth a surface is. Rougher surfaces have more microscopic bumps that interlock, creating more friction. Smoother surfaces have fewer bumps and less friction.": "",
  "What does 'oppose' mean in the phrase 'friction opposes motion'?": "",
  "It acts in the same direction as the motion": "",
  "It acts against or resists the direction of motion": "",
  "It has no relationship to the direction of motion": "",
  "It increases the speed of the motion further": "",
  "To oppose means to act against or resist. Friction opposes motion by pushing in the direction opposite to the object's movement or the direction it would tend to move, slowing it down or preventing motion.": "",
